1 Introduction

1.1 Theoretical Background

One of the central questions in modern community ecology1 is the mechanisms governing composition of local communities (McGill et al. 2006, Laughlin et al. 2020). The accepted theoretical framework suggests that dispersal ability of species predicts colonization of a specific location, while an establishment of viable population is ultimately governed by habitat suitability and interaction with other species (Keddy 1992, Mittelbach and Schemske 2015).

Of interest to community ecologists is to bind individual species characteristics and niche requirements with ecosystem functioning and patterns of diversity (Cadotte et al. 2011, Tilman et al. 2014). One modern approach used in ecology is to examine such patterns through the lens of a functional diversity framework (Diaz and Cabido 2001, Carmona et al. 2016). This approach allows one to view organisms as combinations of unique characteristics, or as points within a multidimensional trait2 space. However, answering questions related to functional diversity requires large quantities of data that identify both species occurrence and their ecological characteristics.

Datasets that contain both occurrence data and species characteristics are available for avian taxa (Johnston et al. 2021, Tobias et al. 2022). Birds are widespread, occur across a spectrum of habitat types, are relatively easy to detect, and are often catalogued by birders, yielding enormous volumes of citizen-science-based data. This makes avian communities an ideal system for studying the mechanisms of environmental filtering.

There are numerous ways by which human population growth affects natural ecosystems, and land use change might be the most direct and certainly one of the most significant facets of global change that put wildlife at risk (Newbold et al. 2015). Land use change affects connectivity among patches of suitable habitats, therefore, dispersal of species (Taylor et al. 1993), and causes a shrink in suitable habitat (Bender et al. 1998). Urbanization represents the most profound degree of land use change a process during which any previously existent habitat is substituted with dense urban infrastructure built-up and the creation of impervious areas (Antrop 2004, Alig et al. 2004, Aronson et al. 2014). When considered as an ecosystem, urbanized areas are not fully sustainable since biodiversity is reduced and critical links missing from healthy food webs primary resources are in short supply and disturbance is too great to maintain biodiversity (McKinney 2002, Palacio et al. 2018).

There is some evidence suggesting that urban environments differentially select certain traits in birds: omnivore, gregarious, sedentary species that prefer forest and cliff habitat have enclosed nests, and large wingspan are more likely to succeed in urban environments (Rodewald and Yahner 2001, Croci et al. 2008). Such suggestions assume that there is environmental filtering by urban habitats (Evans et al. 2018), however it is unclear how general the pattern is across the urbanized areas worldwide.

1.2 Research Questions

In the project presented here, I use a large citizen-science datasets to test the role of different functional traits of bird species in environmental filtering constituted by urban areas at large spatial scales. My aims are:

  • to prepare and clean a dataset describing avian communities in and outside of the cities of Virginia, USA, which would help to develop a toolbox for analysis of larger amounts of data collected at larger scales;

  • to test the role of species functional traits that predict species occurrence within urban environments, which would help to identify a set of traits that play preliminary role in environmental filtering by urban environments;

  • to build a model predicting whether a species is capable to establish a viable population within urban setting based on its functional traits.

1.3 Data

This project requires a combination of three datasets: on bird species occurrence at geographical locations, description of functional traits of these species, and spatial geo-referenced data on land cover for the sites where the species occurred.

To skip the data preparation steps and access the clean dataset used for the further analysis, see the respective section.

1.3.1 Bird occurrence data

There is a considerable population of citizen-science3 contributors, especially in developed countries, who are interested in nature and are willing to share their observations of the wildlife (Sekercioglu 2002). eBird is one of the examples where citizen scientists contribute observations of birds whenever and wherever they observe them, and (as of Mar 2023) managed to collect almost 90 million observations from 860,000 users worldwide. eBird implements the semistructured survey design wherein observers are not given specific instructions regarding data collection, but are required to report some information on sampling effort that would allow the data users to account for the sampling process (Kelling et al. 2019, Callaghan et al. 2021, Johnston et al. 2021).

The dataset is updated monthly and can be accessed at the eBird website4. For this project, I used custom download with the following terms: all species, region of Virginia, USA, all dates5.

To standardize the sampling effort, I cleaned the data prior to usage. Given that the raw data file might be too large to be used (>9 GB), it requires a special package developed by the eBird team, auk (Strimas-Mackey et al. 2020). In this query, I filter the observations that originate from complete checklists6, the data were collected in any year between Mar 15 and Jun 157 and observation took between 1 and 30 minutes.

1.3.2 Birds functional traits data

Each species was described in terms of 23 functional traits reflecting species biotic and abiotic interactions: diet category, diet items, diurnal and nocturnal activity, feeding method, feeding substrate, nest type, nest substrate, breeding system, chick development at hatching, spatial best aggregation, minimum and maximum clutch size, average age at first breeding, number of clutches per year, breeding success, annual survival of adults, mean biomass, maximum life expectancy in the wild, morphological hand-wing index (reflecting the shape of the wing and dispersal abilities), kleptoparasitism (stealing food from other individuals), dependency of nesting on other species, and nest parasitism. This information was obtained from the peer-reviewed literature for each species (Ehrlich et al. 1988, Wilman et al. 2014, Sheard et al. 2020, Billerman et al. 2022); in cases when some information was not available, a trait value was extrapolated based on sister taxa. Different traits had different types of data: some were coded as a continuous variable (e.g., body mass, annual survival, etc.), some as categorical variables (i.e., a species could have only one value of the nest type), and some as discrete distributions (i.e., different diet items or feeding methods were assumed to be more or less preferred by a species).

All these traits were compiled into one dataset describing 703 species of North American avifauna:

traits <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/OleksiiDubovyk/BBSFunRar/main/traits6.csv") %>% as_tibble()

It is important to remember that eBird updates the taxonomy8 annually, while the traits dataset was compiled in fall of 2021. To align taxonomic identities in traits (column ebd_id) with brds (column TAXONOMIC ORDER), we need to track changes in eBird taxonomy updates as there were two major updates in Aug 2021 and Oct 2022 (Clements et al. 2022). Unfortunately, eBird does not maintain records of taxonomy updates anymore, so these files were accessed using Wayback Machine Internet Archive queried images https://www.birds.cornell.edu/clementschecklist/ taken on 16 Apr 2021 (eBird_taxonomy_v2019) and 22 Sep 2022 (eBird_taxonomy_v2021) to download the older taxonomies and align them with the current one (eBird_taxonomy_v2022).

1.3.3 Landcover data

To get the data on land cover, I used MCD12Q1.061 MODIS Land Cover Type Yearly Global data product (Friedl and Sulla-Menashe 2022) which was accessed via Google Earth Engine using the following code:

var year = 2021;
var dataset = ee.ImageCollection('MODIS/061/MCD12Q1');
var igbpLandCover = dataset.select('LC_Type2');
var date = year+'-01-01';
var img = igbpLandCover.filterDate(date).reduce(ee.Reducer.median()).clip(geometry);
Export.image.toDrive({
  image: img,
  description: 'lc_northamerica'+year,
  folder: 'GEE_data',
  scale: 500,
  region: geometry,
  crs: 'EPSG:4326',
  maxPixels: 1e10,
  fileFormat: 'GeoTIFF',
  formatOptions: {
    cloudOptimized: false
  }
  });

Upon download, the following operations were performed to the raw raster in ArcGIS Pro (ESRI 2022): (1) extract by mask of Virginia state boundaries polygon; (2) raster calculator to extract pixels with value 13 which represents urban habitats10 using the expression Con("lc_va" == 13, 1, 0); (3a) raster to polygon with no shape simplification and no multipart features; (3b) raster to polygon applied to discrete raster to create polygons of habitat types across the state; (4) binary urban/non-urban polygons selected by attributes to eliminate non-urban polygons; (5) new attribute field created and geometry area (\(\text{km}^2\)) calculated for each urban polygon; (6) all urban polygons with area less than \(4\text{km}^2\)11 were eliminated with selection by attributes, yielding 45 large patches of urban environment; (7) the events dataset was uploaded as XY point data; (8) events observations were intersected with the urban patches to divide the dataset into urban (treatment) and non-urban (control) observations; (9) the resulting points were intersected again with the polygons of land cover type to get the data about the type of environment where the observations were collected (Fig. 1.1). Finally, the events point dataset was exported as a separate file, which will be named events_lc here.

Figure 1.1: Land cover across Virginia, according to MCD12Q1.061 MODIS Land Cover Type Yearly Global data product, with eBird observations and large urban patches indicated.

1.3.4 Data preparation

For each large urban patch, a list of species that occur within an island should be constructed. To see what species are found outside of these patches and check whether such species colonized into the city, and to account for sampling effort within the patch, a pool of closest number of observations that have been collected within the patch is also pooled from outside (Fig. 1.2).

Figure 1.2: Pooling observations into those collected within and outside of the urban patches in a balanced way. The number of observations is maintained the same between the two groups to construct the species lists and assign species different statuses: 0 if the species that occurs out of the city does not colonize it, 1 if the species that occurs outside of the city is also observed in the city, 2 if the species occurs within the city but is not found outside.

Based on the presence/absence data for each species, it is classified into one of the categories explained in Table 1.1).

Table 1.1: Possible species statuses.
Status Explanation
0 species that occurs out of the city does not colonize that city
1 species that occurs outside of the city is also observed in the city
2 species occurs within the city but is not found outside 
library(geosphere)
cities <- events_lc$Id %>% unique() %>% .[!is.na(.)]
find_closest_points <- function(cityid){
  urb_pool <- events_lc %>%
    filter(Id == cityid)
  n <- nrow(urb_pool)
  clat <- urb_pool$LATITUDE %>% mean()
  clon <- urb_pool$LONGITUDE %>% mean()
  calc_dist <- function(long, lat){
    sapply(1:length(long), function(i){
      geosphere::distHaversine(
      matrix(c(clon, clat, long[i], lat[i]), nrow = 2, ncol = 2, byrow = T),
      r = 6378.137)
    })
  }
  nonurb_pool <- events_lc %>%
    filter(is_urban == 0) %>%
    mutate(dist = calc_dist(LONGITUDE, LATITUDE)) %>%
    arrange(dist) %>%
    as_tibble() %>%
    .[1:n, ] %>%
    mutate(Id = cityid)
  return(nonurb_pool)
}
nonurb_pools <- find_closest_points(cities[1])
for (city in cities[-1]){
  nonurb_pools <- bind_rows(nonurb_pools,
                            find_closest_points(city))
} #takes ~ 8 minutes
write_csv(nonurb_pools, "./data/nonurb_pools.csv")
nonurb_pools <- read_csv("./data/nonurb_pools.csv")

Therefore, it seems justified to parse the observations within the urban patches that have large numbers of observations into groups of 50 observations, which roughly corresponds to the 25th percentile of the number of sampling events per patch.

parse_sampling <- function(dataset){
  n <- nrow(dataset)
  if (n >= 50){
    p <- sample(x = 1:(n%/%50), size = n, replace = T)
  }else{
    p <- rep(1, n)
  }
  dataset %>%
    mutate(parse = p)
}
parsed_events <- bind_rows(events_lc %>% filter(Id == cities[1]) %>% parse_sampling(),
                           nonurb_pools %>% filter(Id == cities[1]) %>% parse_sampling())
for (city in cities[-1]){
  parsed_events <- bind_rows(parsed_events,
                            events_lc %>% filter(Id == city) %>% parse_sampling(),
                            nonurb_pools %>% filter(Id == city) %>% parse_sampling())
}

2.2 Pooling species lists

Now we can use the partitioned lists of sampling events to pools of species observed during those sampling events.

draw_species_sed <- function(sed){
  brds %>%
    filter(`SAMPLING EVENT IDENTIFIER` %in% sed) %>%
    group_by(`TAXONOMIC ORDER`, `COMMON NAME`) %>%
    summarise(abundance = mean(`OBSERVATION COUNT`, na.rm = T),
              freq = n() / length(sed), 
              .groups = "drop")
}
draw_species_pool <- function(pool, urban){
  pool <- pool %>% filter(is_urban == urban)
  draw_species_sed(pool$SAMPLING_EVENT_IDENTIFIER %>% unlist()) %>%
    mutate(is_urban = pool$is_urban[1], patch_id = pool$Id[1], parse = pool$parse[1])
}
parsed_species_lists <- tibble(NA)[0]
parsed_ids <- parsed_events %>% distinct(Id, parse) %>% as.matrix()
for (i in 1:nrow(parsed_ids)){
  parsed_species_lists <- bind_rows(parsed_species_lists,
                                    draw_species_pool(parsed_events %>% 
                                                        filter(Id == parsed_ids[i, 1], parse == parsed_ids[i, 2]), urban = 0),
                                    draw_species_pool(parsed_events %>% 
                                                        filter(Id == parsed_ids[i, 1], parse == parsed_ids[i, 2]), urban = 1))
}

2.3 Clean dataset

Finally, parsed_species_lists can be used to define the status of each species for each partition of urban patches, as it was shown in Fig. 1.2.

assign_status <- function(nonurb, urb){
  nonurb <- nonurb %>%
    group_by(`COMMON NAME`) %>%
    summarise(`TAXONOMIC ORDER` = min(`TAXONOMIC ORDER`[`TAXONOMIC ORDER` %in% traits$ebd_id2022]),
              `COMMON NAME` = `COMMON NAME`[1],
              abundance = sum(abundance),
              freq = sum(freq),
              is_urban = is_urban[1],
              patch_id = patch_id[1],
              parse = parse[1])
  urb <- urb %>%
    group_by(`COMMON NAME`) %>%
    summarise(`TAXONOMIC ORDER` = min(`TAXONOMIC ORDER`[`TAXONOMIC ORDER` %in% traits$ebd_id2022]),
              `COMMON NAME` = `COMMON NAME`[1],
              abundance = sum(abundance),
              freq = sum(freq),
              is_urban = is_urban[1],
              patch_id = patch_id[1],
              parse = parse[1])
  compare <- full_join(nonurb, urb, by = "COMMON NAME", relationship = "one-to-one")
  compare[is.na(compare)] <- 0
  compare %>%
    mutate(status = ifelse(compare$abundance.x > 0 & compare$abundance.y == 0, 0,
                           ifelse(compare$abundance.x > 0 & compare$abundance.x > 0, 1, 
                                  ifelse(compare$abundance.x == 0 & compare$abundance.y > 0, 2, 3))),
           dif_abundance = compare$abundance.x - compare$abundance.y,
           dif_freq = compare$freq.x - compare$freq.y,
           ebd_id2022 = apply(data.frame(compare$`TAXONOMIC ORDER.x`, compare$`TAXONOMIC ORDER.y`), 1, max),
           patch_id = apply(data.frame(compare$patch_id.x, compare$patch_id.y), 1, max),
           parse = apply(data.frame(compare$parse.x, compare$parse.y), 1, max),
           common_name = `COMMON NAME`) %>%
    select(common_name, ebd_id2022, patch_id, parse, status, dif_abundance, dif_freq)
}

parsed_species_statuses <- tibble(NA)[0]
parsed_ids <- parsed_events %>% distinct(Id, parse) %>% as.matrix()
for (i in 1:nrow(parsed_ids)){
  print(i)

                                                                           patch_id == parsed_ids[i, 1],

}

The ultimate clean dataset has 97,786 rows and covers observations of 333 bird species in Virginia, as well as data on 21 functional traits. As we can see on Fig. 2.2-A, species vary in their statuses (Table 1.1) across the partitioned patches: there are several species that have only status 0 (i.e., never colonize urban habitats from outside), and fewer species with status 1 (i.e., do colonize urban patches from outside) or 2 (only occur in urban patches). Statuses of the majority of species are highly variable with expectation between 0 and 1, suggesting that status 2 is somewhat redundant. Mean differences in abundances of species between outside and within an island are close to 0 in most species, however, there is a suite of species that have high variability and positive values of this metric (Fig. 2.2-B), denoting species that have abundance in the cities smaller than outside (i.e., the urban population is a subset of surrounding population). Finally, changes in species frequencies seem to be symmetrical (Fig. 2.2-C).

Figure 2.2: Variability of species statuses and differences in abundance and frequency across urban patches.

Although there is a significant correlation (Spearmans \(\rho = 0.438, p < 0.001\)) between the difference in frequency and difference in abundance among the species, high significance can be explained by the large sample size, as visually there is no linear relationship between these two metrics (Fig. 2.3-A). The positive association between changes in abundance and changes in frequency only become visible when both metrics are transformed with a logistic function. Obviously, both change in abundance and frequency can only be positive for species with status 0 and negative for status 2 (Fig. 2.3-B,C). However, one can see that the variation of difference in abundance of species with status 1 is very high and overlaps with both 0 and 1 (Fig. 2.3-B).

Figure 2.3: Covariation of species statuses and differences in abundance and frequency across urban patches.

3 Modeling and Methodology

To answer the different research questions, different methods should be deployed. Yet, these questions are interconnected to some extent. For example, finding the traits that determine environmental filtering and modeling whether a species can successfully establish a viable population within a city based on species traits manifest different sides of the same model, where species success within urban habitats is explained by combinations of traits (i.e., species descriptors).

For all models in the further analysis, the dataset should be divided into training and test datasets for model building and validation respectively. Luckily, there are more than enough observations to split it into two equal datasets with large amounts of data.

set.seed(1)
idx <- sample(x = 1:2, size = nrow(urb_brds), replace = T)
urb_brds_train <- urb_brds[idx == 1,]
urb_brds_test <- urb_brds[idx == 2,]

3.1 Finding the meaningful traits via dimension reduction

For this section, difference of abundance and difference of frequency of species outside and within an urban patch will be used as a continuous response variable in a model. The main purpose of this section is to reveal species traits that are relevant to environmental filtering and, thus, can predict occurrence of species in urban patches, especially given that it has already been shown that differences of abundance and frequency can be used as proxy to the status of species (Fig. 2.3).

3.1.1 Lasso regression

Using lasso regression, one may determine which predictors contribute poorly to the model, as the model will minimize the error function in such a way as it will set some coefficients to 0. In the setting presented here, one may then conclude that those traits for which coefficients are set to 0 are irrelevant to environmental filtering. First, the optimal tuning parameter \(\lambda\) has to be found.

library(glmnet)
lambda_cands <- 10^seq(-5, 5, by = 0.2)
x <- urb_brds_train[,c("hwi", "mlife", "adsurviv", "matage", "parasi", "egglow", "eggupp", 
                 "suces", "attem", "bmass", "naggr", "ndepen", 
                 "nsbank", "nsgroun", "nsgrass", "nsclif", "nsbuild", "nsshru", 
                 "nsdeci", "nsconi", "nssnag", "nscact", "nstang", "nsfloat",
                 "fsmud", "fswatb", "fswata", "fstimb", "fsgroun", "fsunder", 
                 "fsmidhigh", "fscanopy", "fsaerial", "fsdump",
                 "fpnoct", "fpdiur", "klepto", 
                 "fcinvert", "fcvend", "fcvect", "fcfish", "fcunk", "fcscav", "fcfruit", 
                 "fcnect", "fcseed", "fcgree", "fcleft",
                 "fmdig", "fmgrgl", "fmfogl", "fmbagl", "fmhogl", "fmhopo", "fmhawk", "fmaero", "fmapur",
                 "fmswoo", "fmhipa", "fmlopa", "fmhidi", "fmskim", "fmsdiv", "fmsdip", "fmdabb",
                 "fmstal", "fmprob")] %>% as.data.frame()
y_a <- urb_brds_train$dif_abundance %>% unlist()
y_f <- urb_brds_train$dif_freq %>% unlist()
cv_llm_a <- cv.glmnet(as.matrix(x), y_a, alpha = 1, lambda = lambda_cands, nfolds = 10)
cv_llm_f <- cv.glmnet(as.matrix(x), y_f, alpha = 1, lambda = lambda_cands, nfolds = 10)
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(cv_llm_a, main = "Abundance")
plot(cv_llm_f, main = "Frequency")

Both plots suggest that the optimal \(\lambda\)s are low, which implies that the lasso models will be close to the least-squares regression.

set.seed(1)
lasso_best_lambdas <- c("lambda_a" = cv_llm_a$lambda[which(cv_llm_a$cvm == min(cv_llm_a$cvm))],
  "lambda_f" = cv_llm_f$lambda[which(cv_llm_f$cvm == min(cv_llm_f$cvm))])
llm_a <- glmnet(as.matrix(x), y_a, alpha = 1, lambda = lasso_best_lambdas["lambda_a"], standardize = T)

3.1.2 Principal component analysis regression

The variety of birds traits used (Table 6.1) suggest that there is some redundancy in them. Indeed, biologically, one could predict that traits like fc_categ (diet category with levels: FruiNect, Invertebrate, Omnivore, PlantSeed, VertFishScav) will covary with variables of distribution of diet items (e.g., FruiNect will be positively associated with fcfruit, fcnect, fcseed, etc.) Moreover, it can be expected that different traits are related, for example, feeding method and diet items (e.g., it would be unlikely that a species that primarily consumes nectar and green part of plants obtains the food through high gliding and aerial pursuit or finds the food items in the air rather than on trees and in canopy). Therefore, there should be utility in dimension reduction that would account for high covariation between some variables.

set.seed(1)
library(pls)

pcr_f_all <- pls::pcr(y_f ~ ., data = cbind(y_f, x), scale = T, validation = "CV")

validationplot(pcr_a_all, val.type = "MSEP", main = "Abundance")
validationplot(pcr_f_all, val.type = "MSEP", main = "Frequency")

The validation plots suggest that the expectations do not reflect reality and few principal components cannot explain the variance of difference of either abundance or frequency of species.

For the former model, we can see that \(\approx 100 \%\) of variance of difference in abundance are explained by \(M = 63\), which is close to \(p = 67\). However, \(\approx 95 \%\) of variance can be explained by the first \(M = 42\) principal components and \(\approx 90 \%\) of variance can be explained by the first \(M = 36\) principal components. In other words, loosing \(10 \%\) of explained variance by cutting off half of the variables might provide some insight onto what traits contribute the most to the occurrence of species in urban settings.

PCR cannot be used for variable selection per se. However, loadings of variables reflect contribution of these variables to the principal components, which can be used to draw inference about relative importance of different traits. By default, pls::pcr()$loadings does not print some loadings, and in ?stats::loadings we see that Small loadings are conventionally not printed (replaced by spaces), to draw the eye to the pattern of the larger loadings. It is unclear, though, what loading value is small enough to be neglected. Here we read: Field (2005) advocates the suggestion of Guadagnoli & Velicer (1988) to regard a factor as reliable if it has four or more loadings of at least 0.6 regardless of sample size. Stevens (1992) suggests using a cut-off of 0.4, irrespective of sample size, for interpretative purposes. (Guadagnoli and Velicer 1988, Stevens 1992, Field 2005)

pcr_a <- pcr(y_a ~ ., data = cbind(y_a, x), scale = T, ncomp = 36)
pcr_a_l <- pcr_a$loadings
pcr_a_l <- data.frame(matrix(as.numeric(pcr_a_l), attributes(pcr_a_l)$dim, dimnames = attributes(pcr_a_l)$dimnames))
pcr_a_l_large <- apply(pcr_a_l, 1, function(x) sum(abs(x)>= 0.4))
names(pcr_a_l_large)[pcr_a_l_large != 0]

From this we can argue that nesting success, nesting on certain substrates (deciduous trees, cacti, tangles), feeding in air, being diurnal, having certain diet (vertebrates or nectar) and methods of feeding (digging, aerial foliage, aerial pursuit, skimming or dipping) are the traits that affect changes of species abundance along an urban gradient.

These results are different from PCR. They suggest that trait variance within such traits as nest substrate (coniferous trees, cacti), feeding substrate (mud, ground, air, dumps), feeding time (nigh), and methods (ground glean, aerial foliage, probing) are sufficient to predict whether a species will have a different abundance within and outside of cities.

Unlike PCR, where modeling both difference of abundance and frequency of species yielded the same results, PLSR suggests that different traits determine shift of abundance and frequency. In the latter case, governing are the following: nest parasitism, nest success, nest substrate (grass, cliffs, snags), feeding substrate (mud, timber, air), diet items (warm-blooded vertebrates, fish, green parts of vegetation, human leftovers), and feeding methods (aerial foliage, high patrol, and dabbing).

There are many traits selected as those having a non-zero effect on odds of a species having an increase or decrease in abundance and frequency outside of the city and within a city. Yet, it should be understood that such results are not reliable given that the inference based on a generalized linear models is sensitive to the same assumptions as a linear model, and at least one of the assumptions (i.e., no multicollinearity) is not met.

3.1.5 Variable selection

Model selection from a pool of random combinations of predictors (i.e., data dredging, stepwise analysis) is considered a poor practice and a statistical misuse in ecology (Whittingham et al. 2006). With that in mind, I will proceed with that very approach.

library(leaps)
regfit_fwd_a <- regsubsets(y_a ~ ., data = cbind(y_a, x), method = "forward")
## Reordering variables and trying again:
regfit_fwd_a_summary <- summary(regfit_fwd_a)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(regfit_fwd_a_summary$rss, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = "RSS", type = "l")
plot(regfit_fwd_a_summary$adjr2, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = expression(R[adj]^2), type="l")
plot(regfit_fwd_a_summary$cp, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = expression(C[p]), type= 'l')
plot(regfit_fwd_a_summary$bic, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = "BIC", type = 'l')

regfit_bwd_a <- regsubsets(y_a ~ ., data = cbind(y_a, x), method = "backward")
## Reordering variables and trying again:
regfit_bwd_a_summary <- summary(regfit_bwd_a)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(regfit_bwd_a_summary$rss, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = "RSS", type = "l")
plot(regfit_bwd_a_summary$adjr2, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = expression(R[adj]^2), type="l")
plot(regfit_bwd_a_summary$cp, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = expression(C[p]), type= 'l')
plot(regfit_bwd_a_summary$bic, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = "BIC", type = 'l')

In the case of changes in species frequency, the results of forward and backward subset selection are inconclusive. The only traits that are selected by both approach is feeding in middle to high parts of trees. The increase of \(R^2_{adj}\) and decrease of RSS, BIC, and \(C_p\) with number of variables in a subset seem monotonic, which suggests that the selected subset is doubtfully better than any other.

3.1.6 Regression tree

All previous methods were only used with predictors representing those traits that can be quantified as a continuous variable. Yet, there are some traits that can only be coded as a factor variable (e.g., breeding system is either cooperative, lekking, monogamous, polyandrous, polygamous, polygynous, or promiscuous, and so on; see Table 6.1):

levels(traits$brsys %>% as.factor())
## [1] "coop"    "lek"     "monog"   "polyand" "polygam" "polygyn" "promisc"
levels(traits$dev %>% as.factor())
## [1] "alt"      "pre2"     "pre3"     "pre4"     "semialt1" "semialt2" "semipre"
levels(traits$fc_categ %>% as.factor())
## [1] "FruiNect"     "Invertebrate" "Omnivore"     "PlantSeed"    "VertFishScav"
levels(traits$nest %>% as.factor())
##  [1] "burrow"   "cavity"   "chamber"  "crevice"  "cup"      "gourd"   
##  [7] "no"       "oven"     "paras"    "pend"     "platform" "saucer"  
## [13] "scrape"   "sphere"

Unlike the methods already considered earlier, decision trees are suitable for incorporating such variables.

3.1.7 Comparison of the models

Now, having the following list of models:

  • llm_a, llm_f: Lasso regression with formula y_a ~ x and y_f ~ x, respectively,

  • pcr_a, pcr_f: PCR regression with formula y_a ~ x and y_f ~ x, respectively,

  • pls_a, pls_f: PLS regression with formula y_a ~ x and y_f ~ x, respectively,

  • logit_a, logit_f: logistic regression with formula logit(y_a > 0) ~ x and logit(y_f > 0) ~ x, respectively,

  • regfit_fwd_a, regfit_bwd_a, regfit_fwd_f, regfit_bwd_f: multivariate regression with subsets of predictors selected via forward (*_fwd_*) and backward (*_bwd_*) selection algorithm,

  • tree_f: regression tree with formula y_f ~ x_full,

we can compare the prediction capabilities of them using the test part of the dataset, urb_brds_test. We should keep in mind, however, that for the models to be comparable in terms of their error rates, the response should be the same, which is not the case for logit_* and tree_f, so that these models should be considered separately.

predict_regsubset <- function(reg, x){
  coefs <- coef(reg, which.min(summary(reg)$bic))
  x <- as.matrix(cbind(`(Intercept)` = 1, x))
  x[, names(coefs)] %*% coefs
}
regression_predictions <- tibble(
  y_llm_a = predict(llm_a, newx = test_x %>% as.matrix()) %>% unlist(),
  y_llm_f = predict(llm_f, newx = test_x %>% as.matrix()) %>% unlist(),
  y_pcr_a = predict(pcr_a, test_x %>% as.matrix(), ncomp = pcr_a$ncomp) %>% unlist(),
  y_pcr_f = predict(pcr_f, test_x %>% as.matrix(), ncomp = pcr_f$ncomp) %>% unlist(),
  y_pls_a = predict(pls_a, test_x %>% as.matrix(), ncomp = pls_a$ncomp) %>% unlist(),
  y_pls_f = predict(pls_f, test_x %>% as.matrix(), ncomp = pls_f$ncomp) %>% unlist(),
  y_regfit_fwd_a = predict_regsubset(regfit_fwd_a, test_x) %>% unlist(),
  y_regfit_bwd_a = predict_regsubset(regfit_bwd_a, test_x) %>% unlist(),
  y_regfit_fwd_f = predict_regsubset(regfit_fwd_f, test_x) %>% unlist(),
  y_regfit_bwd_f = predict_regsubset(regfit_bwd_f, test_x) %>% unlist()
)

If the response variables are considered as a binary response (i.e., if a change of species abundance or frequency larger or smaller than zero), backward subset selection still yields the most accurate prediction, but logistic regression might be a better option to predict whether a species frequency will change in urban patches based on its traits. In both cases the prediction accuracy is only slightly different from random (i.e., 0.5).

3.2 Modeling species statuses with unsupervised learning

The poor performance of the models in the previous section can be explained by the fact that data preparation steps were primarily designed to build a model that predicts a discrete status of species relative to its reaction to urbanization (e.g., urban dwellers that only exist in urban habitats, urban avoiders that never colonize urban habitats from surrounding natural areas, or adapters that occur in both types of habitats). This section is dedicated to such predictions.

3.2.1 K-Nearest neighbors classification

The data on predictors is already ready for analysis, so it only needs to be plugged into a model. Yet, first we need to pick the optimal \(K\) value. Unfortunately, class:knn works very slowly for large datasets, so other libraries should be used and the training dataset size should be reduced. Also, all factor variables should be transformed into sets of dummy variables.

# library(devtools)
# install_github("davpinto/fastknn")
library(fastknn)
set.seed(1)
x_knn <- cbind(x, 
               model.matrix( ~ brsys - 1, data = x_full), 
               model.matrix( ~ dev - 1, data = x_full),
               model.matrix( ~ fc_categ - 1, data = x_full),
               model.matrix( ~ nest - 1, data = x_full))
y_knn <- as.factor(urb_brds_train$status %>% unlist())
shrink_knn <- sample(1:nrow(x_knn), 5000, F)
x_knn_sub <- x_knn[shrink_knn,]
y_knn_sub <- y_knn[shrink_knn]
knn_cv <- fastknnCV(x = as.matrix(x_knn_sub), y = y_knn_sub, 
                    k = seq(1, 501, 25), folds = 5, method = "dist", eval.metric = "mean_error", 
                    normalize = "std")
plot(knn_cv$cv_table$k, knn_cv$cv_table$mean, type = "l", 
     main = paste("Best K =", knn_cv$cv_table$k[which(knn_cv$cv_table$mean == min(knn_cv$cv_table$mean))]),
     xlab = "K", ylab = "Mean error, 5-fold CV")
points(knn_cv$cv_table$k[which(knn_cv$cv_table$mean == min(knn_cv$cv_table$mean))], min(knn_cv$cv_table$mean), col = "red", pch = 16)

Now, a KNN classifier with \(K = 125\) will be tested on the entire dataset:

set.seed(1)
x_test_knn <- cbind(test_x, 
               model.matrix( ~ brsys - 1, data = test_x_full), 
               model.matrix( ~ dev - 1, data = test_x_full),
               model.matrix( ~ fc_categ - 1, data = test_x_full),
               model.matrix( ~ nest - 1, data = test_x_full))
knn_status <- fastknn(xtr = x_knn %>% as.matrix(), ytr = y_knn, 
                      xte = x_test_knn[, colnames(x_test_knn) %in% colnames(x_knn)] %>% as.matrix(),
        k = 125, normalize = "std", method = "dist")
table(knn_status$class, urb_brds_test$status %>% as.factor())
##    
##         0     1     2
##   0  9751  2843  3142
##   1  4113 24202  2293
##   2   856   412  1138
mean(knn_status$class == urb_brds_test$status %>% as.factor())
## [1] 0.7198154

The KNN classifier performs fairly well, accurately predicting species status based on its traits in \(72\%\) of cases. However, it is notable that this classifier tends to misclassify species with status 0 (occur outside but not within the city) and 1 (occur in both habitats) as those with status 2 (occur only in cities) much more frequently than species that really have status 2.

For a sake of experiment and to validate the results of the previous section, I will run the model again, but using only those traits that were selected as important for environmental filtering.

set.seed(1)
x_knn_lim <- x_knn[, c("fcleft", "fmbagl", "fstimb", "fsunder", "fswata", "fswatb", "naggr",
                       "adsurviv", "bmass", "egglow", "fcgree", "fcinvert", "fcvend", "fmaero",
                       "fmapur", "fmdabb", "fmdig", "fmgrgl", "fmhawk", "fmhidi", "fmhipa", "fmsdip", "fmsdiv", 
                       "fmskim", "fmstal", "fpdiur", "hwi", "klepto", "matage", "mlife", "nsbank",
                       "nsbuild", "nscact", "nsdeci", "nsgrass", "nsgroun", "nsshru", "nssnag", "nstang", "parasi")]
knn_status_lim <- fastknn(xtr = x_knn_lim %>% as.matrix(), ytr = y_knn, 
                      xte = x_test_knn[, colnames(x_test_knn) %in% colnames(x_knn_lim)] %>% as.matrix(),
        k = 125, normalize = "std", method = "dist")
table(knn_status_lim$class, urb_brds_test$status %>% as.factor())
mean(knn_status_lim$class == urb_brds_test$status %>% as.factor())

Now we can see that if we limit the predictors to those selected by backward subset selection to predict change in species abundance and by logistic regression to predict binary response of change in species frequency, the KNN classifier perform even more poorly than a random class selection.

  1. ecological community is a set of populations of different species that occupy the same location at the same time; community ecology relies heavily on mathematical and statistical approaches due to omnipresent statistical noise in the data describing complex multi-species systems

  2. functional trait is a characteristic of a species or individual that affects its fitness to the environment; in other words, it is a descriptor of a biological organism (i.e., color, body mass, diet, morphometrics etc.)

  3. citizen science is a scientific research framework which incorporates data collection and analysis conducted by lay citizens

  4. free access to the data requires an annual approval from the database management team to be able to either download a subset of the data or the whole dataset at once (>140 GB)

  5. the request was submitted and approved on 31 Mar 2023, download raw data here, however, the download link might be inactive; prepackaged sampling event data were downloaded for the entire world on 31 Mar 2023

  6. i.e., observers indicated that all species that could be identified were reported, so that there is no reason to expect false-absence of species in such observation

  7. Mar 15Jun 15 which covers breeding season of most birds in Virginia

  8. taxonomy here denotes the identities of species; as species identities are coded as integers, it is highly important to account for any changes, since otherwise it would cause referring to one species as if it was a different species

  9. references are coded as following: Billerman et al.2022 (B), Ehrlich et al.1988 (E), Sheard et al.2020 (S), and Wilman et al.2014 (W)

  10. as per the MCD12Q1 description, pixel value 13 denotes urban and built-up lands: at least 30% impervious surface area including building materials, asphalt and vehicles

  11. the area of 4 square kilometers constitutes the 5th percentile of urban areas in the U.S. according to the [2019 TIGER/Line Shapefiles data]^(https://www.census.gov/geographies/mapping-files/time-series/geo/tiger-line-file.html)

  12. the results are very close to the previous model; probably, it can be explained by strong correlation found (see Fig. 2.3) between differences in abundance and frequency
